<p>In <a href="/wiki/Greek_historiography" title="Greek historiography">Greek historiography</a>, <b>Damon and Pythias</b> (or <b>Phintias</b>) is a legend surrounding the <a href="/wiki/Pythagoreanism" title="Pythagoreanism">Pythagorean</a> ideal of friendship. Damon is accused of a plot against the tyrannical <a href="/wiki/Dionysius_I_of_Syracuse" title="Dionysius I of Syracuse">Dionysius I of Syracuse</a>. He is condemned but allowed to settle his affairs on the condition that he leaves his friend as a hostage. Damon's returning to face execution in order to redeem his friend causes Dionysus to pardon him.</p>
<p></p>
